---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section
  id="why"
  class="border-y border-neutral-900 bg-neutral-900/40 px-6 py-20 md:py-28"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
        <span class="text-neutral-600">01</span> The question
      </p>
      <h2
        class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        Why would you need one?
      </h2>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        <p>
          The clearest way to answer that is a story most developers have
          already lived, told through React. You started with the core: React
          rendered components and turned events into more components, and that
          was it. To build a real application you stitched the rest on yourself.
          You picked a router. You picked a data-fetching layer. You added a UI
          component library, then a design system on top of it. It worked. But
          it was a lot of work, and <mark>none of it transferred</mark>. Switch
          teams, switch companies, and you rebuilt the same setup from scratch,
          differently every time.
        </p>
        <p>
          Meta-frameworks solved this. Next.js, and later TanStack Start, took
          all that plumbing and put it in a batteries-included box you could
          move with. You still wrote React, but routing, rendering, and data
          access arrived already arranged, so setting up a serious app stopped
          being someone's personal side quest.
        </p>
        <p>
          Harnesses today are the React core. They are excellent at the one
          universal thing they do, and everyone is stitching the rest on by
          hand: custom CLIs, code mode, skills, glue scripts to make an agent
          reach beyond the folder in front of it. It works, and it does not
          transfer.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <VizPlaceholder
          label="React core with hand-stitched router, data, UI, design system, resolving into a single batteries-included box, then the same shape redrawn for harnesses"
          ratio="aspect-[4/3]"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <figure class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl border-t border-neutral-800 pt-10 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-medium leading-snug text-neutral-100 sm:text-3xl">
        A meta-harness is the <span class="text-accent">Next.js of harnesses</span>.
      </p>
      <figcaption class="mt-4 text-lg text-neutral-400">
        The box that arranges the pieces, so you can stop building the setup and
        start doing the work.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>
</section>
